{"id":4537,"date":"2023-12-08T15:33:39","date_gmt":"2023-12-08T04:33:39","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.stokefoiling.com\/?post_type=help_centre&#038;p=4537"},"modified":"2023-12-08T15:34:42","modified_gmt":"2023-12-08T04:34:42","slug":"crashing-safely-on-the-stoke-foil","status":"publish","type":"help_centre","link":"https:\/\/www.stokefoiling.com\/help-centre\/safety\/crashing-safely-on-the-stoke-foil\/","title":{"rendered":"Crashing Safely on the Stoke Foil"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>Navigating the Stoke Foil involves a learning curve, and understanding how to crash safely is key to ensuring your well-being and protecting your equipment. Here are some things to consider:<\/p><ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><li><strong>Losing Balance<\/strong><\/li><\/ul><p>If you sense that you are losing balance on the Stoke Foil, the best approach is not to try to save it. Instead, allow yourself to fall off in the same direction as the imbalance. Attempting to recover may increase the risk of injury or damage to the equipment.<\/p><ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><li><strong>Avoid Jumping Off or Pushing<\/strong><\/li><\/ul><p>In a potential crash, it&#8217;s crucial not to jump off the board or push away. These actions can lead to uncontrolled movements and may result in injuries or damage to the foil. Instead, focus on falling off the board in a controlled manner away from your gear.<\/p><ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><li><strong>Release the Trigger<\/strong><\/li><\/ul><p>When you realise a crash is looming, release the trigger to disengage the motor. This step is essential for safety, ensuring the motor is no longer propelling the foil. It allows you to separate from the board without any additional force from the motor.<\/p>","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Navigating the Stoke Foil involves a learning curve, and understanding how to crash safely is key to ensuring your well-being and protecting your equipment. Here are some things to consider: If you sense that you 